I now have all the information needed. Let me compile a comprehensive summary of everything required for implementing `FalconSigner`.

---

Here is everything you need to implement `FalconSigner` in starknet.js v9 (version 9.2.1).

## 1. `SignerInterface` — abstract class to extend

Located at line 1075 of `/home/felt/PycharmProjects/s2morrow/apps/demo/node_modules/starknet/dist/index.d.ts`:

```typescript
declare abstract class SignerInterface {
  abstract getPubKey(): Promise<string>;
  abstract signMessage(typedData: TypedData, accountAddress: string): Promise<Signature>;
  abstract signTransaction(transactions: Call[], transactionsDetail: InvocationsSignerDetails): Promise<Signature>;
  abstract signDeployAccountTransaction(transaction: DeployAccountSignerDetails): Promise<Signature>;
  abstract signDeclareTransaction(transaction: DeclareSignerDetails): Promise<Signature>;
}
```

`Signature = string[] | WeierstrassSignatureType` — you return `string[]` (array of hex felts).

---

## 2. `InvocationsSignerDetails` — what `signTransaction` receives

```typescript
type InvocationsSignerDetails = V3InvocationsSignerDetails & {
  version: `${ETransactionVersion}`;  // e.g. "0x3"
  skipValidate?: boolean;
};

type V3InvocationsSignerDetails = V3TransactionDetails & {
  walletAddress: string;       // sender account address
  cairoVersion: CairoVersion;  // "0" | "1" | undefined
  chainId: StarknetChainId;    // e.g. "0x534e5f4d41494e"
  version: `${ETransactionVersion3}`;
};

type V3TransactionDetails = {
  nonce: BigNumberish;
  version: BigNumberish;
  resourceBounds: ResourceBoundsBN;
  tip: BigNumberish;
  paymasterData: BigNumberish[];
  accountDeploymentData: BigNumberish[];
  nonceDataAvailabilityMode: EDataAvailabilityMode;  // "L1" | "L2"
  feeDataAvailabilityMode: EDataAvailabilityMode;
};

// ResourceBoundsBN keys match ResourceBounds with bigint values
type ResourceBoundsBN = {
  [K in keyof ResourceBounds]: { [P in keyof ResourceBounds[K]]: bigint }
};
// In practice for V3: { l1_gas: {max_amount: bigint, max_price_per_unit: bigint}, l2_gas: {...}, l1_data_gas: {...} }
```

---

## 3. `DeployAccountSignerDetails`

```typescript
type DeployAccountSignerDetails = V3DeployAccountSignerDetails;

type V3DeployAccountSignerDetails = Required<DeployAccountContractPayload> & V3TransactionDetails & {
  contractAddress: BigNumberish;
  chainId: StarknetChainId;
  version: `${ETransactionVersion3}`;
};

type DeployAccountContractPayload = {
  classHash: string;
  constructorCalldata?: RawArgs;
  addressSalt?: BigNumberish;
  contractAddress?: string;
};
// So V3DeployAccountSignerDetails has:
//   classHash, constructorCalldata, addressSalt, contractAddress (all required)
//   + nonce, version, resourceBounds, tip, paymasterData, accountDeploymentData,
//     nonceDataAvailabilityMode, feeDataAvailabilityMode
//   + chainId
```

---

## 4. `DeclareSignerDetails`

```typescript
type DeclareSignerDetails = V3DeclareSignerDetails & {
  version: `${ETransactionVersion}`;
};

type V3DeclareSignerDetails = V3TransactionDetails & {
  classHash: string;
  compiledClassHash: string;
  senderAddress: string;
  chainId: StarknetChainId;
  version: `${ETransactionVersion3}`;
};
```

---

## 5. How the canonical `Signer` computes transaction hashes

From the `.mjs` source (lines 9442–9492), the canonical `Signer` does the following:

### `signTransaction`

```typescript
async signTransaction(transactions: Call[], details: InvocationsSignerDetails): Promise<Signature> {
  // Step 1: compile calls to calldata
  const compiledCalldata = getExecuteCalldata(transactions, details.cairoVersion);
  // Step 2: compute hash
  const msgHash = hash.calculateInvokeTransactionHash({
    ...details,
    senderAddress: details.walletAddress,
    compiledCalldata,
    version: details.version,
    nonceDataAvailabilityMode: intDAM(details.nonceDataAvailabilityMode),  // "L1"->0, "L2"->1
    feeDataAvailabilityMode: intDAM(details.feeDataAvailabilityMode),
  });
  return this.signRaw(msgHash);
}
```

`intDAM` converts `EDataAvailabilityMode` ("L1"/"L2") to `EDAMode` (0/1). In your implementation you do the same conversion.

### `signDeployAccountTransaction`

```typescript
async signDeployAccountTransaction(details: DeployAccountSignerDetails): Promise<Signature> {
  const compiledConstructorCalldata = CallData.compile(details.constructorCalldata);
  const msgHash = hash.calculateDeployAccountTransactionHash({
    ...details,
    salt: details.addressSalt,
    compiledConstructorCalldata,
    version: details.version,
    nonceDataAvailabilityMode: intDAM(details.nonceDataAvailabilityMode),
    feeDataAvailabilityMode: intDAM(details.feeDataAvailabilityMode),
  });
  return this.signRaw(msgHash);
}
```

### `signDeclareTransaction`

```typescript
async signDeclareTransaction(details: DeclareSignerDetails): Promise<Signature> {
  const msgHash = hash.calculateDeclareTransactionHash({
    ...details,
    version: details.version,
    nonceDataAvailabilityMode: intDAM(details.nonceDataAvailabilityMode),
    feeDataAvailabilityMode: intDAM(details.feeDataAvailabilityMode),
  });
  return this.signRaw(msgHash);
}
```

---

## 6. Hash functions in the `hash` namespace (`import { hash } from 'starknet'`)

The `hash` export is `index$3`. It exposes the **object-form** wrappers from `src/utils/hash/transactionHash/index.ts`:

```typescript
// Object-form (recommended — accepts a single args object):
hash.calculateInvokeTransactionHash(args: {
  senderAddress: BigNumberish;
  version: `${ETransactionVersion3}`;   // "0x3"
  compiledCalldata: Calldata;           // string[]
  chainId: StarknetChainId;
